		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <span id=>Anonymous</span></a><b><span id=></span></b>
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Anonymous&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>:)&nbsp;&nbsp;First, let me say bards can duel well, but they can't duel (that I've found) in what many people call "honorable".  Bards cannot out-melee warriors, monks, pallys or sks.  They weren't created to out-melee them.  Instead, bards use a variety of songs to win.  <br>Bard excel at dot kiting and charming.  Many people say this type of fighting is "not fair" yet they don't expect enchanters to match a warrior for melee, the don't expect a wizard to take a pally's blows or shamans to bash it out with monks.  I tell anyone who challenges me to a duel that if I win, they will lose xp (dotting and charming both make people lose xp during duels).  Some get upset and call me unfair, but they don't realize that bards are really enchanter/melee types with weaknesses and strengths of both.  We mezz and charm well, and we should be able to use those skills in battle.  We have a series of dots that intelligent bards know are wonderful to twist while soloing.  You don't usually see a bard soloing a blue by wacking it to death (unless you're low lvl).<br>So summary: yes, bards duel well, if the bard uses the right combination of songs.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8"></td></tr></table>
